					<h2>Actions to Consider</h2>
					<ul>
						<li>You'll normally wait until your quarter is over to see what went wrong: why opportunities slipped, how they dropped in value, and why some projected opportunities were in fact lost. This can be valuable for future forecast periods. But it may be even more valuable to review historical behavior at the start of the quarter and apply the lessons learned to this period’s forecast.</li>
						<li>Establish a rhythm with each of the sales team – we'd recommend monthly – where you review the progress of deals that were projected 30, 60, and 90 days ago, and examine any unexpected movement in those deals.</li>
					</ul>
					<div class="more_info">
						<ul>
							<li>Check Projected opportunities that moved backwards (to Possible, or Unlikely) or were Lost.  If this pattern is common across the sales team, it usually means a poorly defined sales process, poor qualification practices, or an ineffective discovery or customer alignment. If it is limited to just one or two sellers, coaching is required.</li>
							<li>Dig into the detail of any opportunities that were Projected 90 days ago, and still are. Establish whether there has been any progress through the pipeline states. If there has been none, this means there is probably no Customer Compelling Event.</li>
							<li>Check for opportunities that were Unlikely (or Possible, depending on the timeframe you are looking at) but have been Won. This suggests that the salesperson may not have been fully aware of what is going on in the opportunity, or that they were entering  data into the system at too late a stage, or that they were not maintaining the data. If the system is not up to date, it is very difficult for the sales manager or sales person to achieve an accurate sales forecast, and everyone’s time is wasted.</li>
	   					</ul>
					</div>
					<p><a href="javascript:void[0]" class="more_info_link">More...</a></p>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li class="clearfix">
